grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H022945/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research examined how wealth is created and distributed in the global sugar industry. In doing so it built upon my doctoral research on the international trade regime in sugar. This was&amp;nbsp; published at the beginning of this award by Palgrave Macmillan under the title &lt;i>Sugar : refined power in a global regime&lt;/i>.&lt;br />&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The post-doctoral research looked in particular at the role of sugar processors in determining how sugar cane/beet is grown and processed and how these decisions affect rural economies. Given that over 100 million people are supported worldwide by the sugar industry, the question of who sets the terms of competition for production is of vital importance in better understanding how agriculture relates to development. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Two case studies are used to illustrate the different debates and linkages that characterise contemporary sugar production. The first considers the UK sugar industry and the 'ethical turn' made by British Sugar and Tate &amp;amp; Lyle in moving toward low-carbon and fair trade production models. The second looks at the recent investment in sugar cane and ethanol plantations in southern Africa. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>These studies helped reveal the new patterns of international trade taking shape, and compared the trade-offs between growth and inequality, and carbon reduction and protectionism. As a result, qualitative insights were offered into how rural poverty and environmental degradation could be alleviated through better regulation and institutional design. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>75088</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>96E7209A-255B-4D90-8C91-CDBD779118E6</gtr:id><gtr:title>Big Sugar in southern Africa: rural development and the perverted potential of sugar/ethanol exports.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Journal of peasant studies</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/b070c0d9dad25eb714c725ab6ba9e4e5"><gtr:id>b070c0d9dad25eb714c725ab6ba9e4e5</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Richardson B</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0306-6150</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>pm_53cbfcebfcec12467</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>A7DAEA42-89C6-4E23-8EA2-778EF1E6DBA0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Fair trade and ethical sugar : a firm-centred analysis of market morality</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gt